{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01EyGNs4JSi76NLoKAifesVY","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is TLS authentication failure. Node 3 (crdb-cluster-2) can't connect to nodes 0 and 1 because of TLS issues: \"TLSInfo is not available in request context [code 16/Unauthenticated]\".\n\nThis is happening because nodes 0 and 1 haven't been restarted yet (they still have the old certs loaded in memory), while node 2 (which was the first to be restarted in the rolling restart) has the new cert. \n\nWait, actually in a rolling restart, CockroachDB is being restarted one at a time. \n\nThe problem is that Kubernetes mounts secrets as volumes, and when a secret updates, the mounted files refresh within a few seconds to a couple minutes. So nodes 0 and 1 might have picked up the new cert from the volume even though they haven't been restarted yet, or they could still be running with the old cert in memory if the volume hasn't synced. I need to figure out which scenario is actually happening here.\n\nThe real issue is that CockroachDB loads certificates at startup and keeps them in memory—updating the secret volume doesn't automatically reload them in a running process. So in this rolling restart, node 2 got restarted with the new cert, but nodes 0 and 1 are still using the old one in memory. When node 2 tries to connect to the others with its new cert, there could be a mismatch, though the CA cert is the same so both should be valid.\n\nBut the error \"TLSInfo is not available in request context\" is a gRPC-level error, not a certificate validation failure, so I need to dig deeper into what's actually happening at the gRPC layer. So the readiness probe failure might be what's triggering the restart loop—the node can't pass its readiness check because it can't connect to the other nodes via gRPC to join the cluster. The \"TLSInfo is not available\" error could mean nodes 0 and 1 haven't been r