{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011CDVLqBBNisJx5V6L798L1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I see the real error:\n\n```\ntls: failed to verify certificate: x509: certificate signed by unknown authority\n```\n\nThis is the critical error. When pod 2 (which restarted with new certs) connects to pod 1, it gets \"certificate signed by unknown authority\". But wait, both old and new certs are signed by the SAME CA (the one in `/tmp/certs/ca.crt`)...\n\nUnless! The CA cert in the `cockroachdb-certs` secret is DIFFERENT from the CA cert in `/tmp/certs/ca.crt`. Let me check.\nAh, that's the problem! The two secrets have completely different CA certs backing them. The original `cockroachdb-certs` secret was set up with one CA, while the new `crdb-cluster-certs` secret uses a different CA from `/tmp/certs/`. So when I generated the new node cert signed by the new CA, pod 1 couldn't verify it because it's still trusting the old CA.\n\nThe solution is to update the `ca.crt` in the `cockroachdb-certs` secret to match the CA from `/tmp/certs/` so both secrets are using the same certificate authority.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1894,"cache_read_input_tokens":46897,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1894},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5584a478-d99e-4919-8ac1-94a851f842be","uuid":"873bf381-21b2-41d5-81a2-1b6c65c1e46f","request_id":"req_011Cc9Zrtdd7YKst5tEC3KbV"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011CDVLqBBNisJx5V6L798L1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The error is `certificate signed by unknown authority` — the `cockroachdb-certs` secret has a different CA cert than the one used to sign the new node certs. I need to also update the `ca.crt` in that secret."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1894,"cache_read_input_tokens":46897,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1894},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5584a478-d99e-4919-8ac1-94a851f842be","uuid":"3ee47da0-b729-45f6-859e-0b31d3ac60f3","request_id":"req_011Cc9Zrtdd7YKst5tEC3KbV"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011CDVLqBBNisJx5V6L798L1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01PibBxtbNFecqMxA94eYw8U","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"# Compare the CA cert in the secret vs the one in the toolbox\necho \"=== Secret CA cert ===\" && kubectl -n cockroachdb get secret cockroachdb-certs -o jsonpath='{.data.ca\\.crt}' | base64 -d | openssl x509 -noout -subject -issuer -fingerprint -sha256 -dates\necho \"=== Toolbox CA cert ===\" && kubectl -n cockroachdb exec openssl-toolbox -- openssl x509 -noout -subject -issuer -fingerprint -sha256 -dates -in /tmp/certs/ca.crt","description":"Compare CA certs to confirm they are different"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1894,"cache_read_input_tokens":46897,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1894},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"5584a478-d99e-4919-8ac1-94a851f842be","uuid":"4f0e3960-6e5a-4a3e-9ecd-449154902c8f","request_id":"req_011Cc9Zrtdd7YKst5tEC3KbV"}
